Google Earnings
---------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-07-25/alphabe=
t-gains-on-revenue-beat-from-google-search-advertising ) :

Google parent Alphabet Inc. reported second-quarter revenue that exceeded a=
nalysts=E2=80=99 expectations, boosted by advertising on the company=E2=80=
=99s flagship search business, which is withstanding new competition from a=
rtificial intelligence chatbots. Alphabet=E2=80=99s sales, excluding partne=
r payouts, were $62 billion in the quarter, the company said Tuesday in a s=
tatement. Analysts had projected $60.2 billion, according to data compiled =
by Bloomberg. Search advertising performed well, generating $42.6 billion, =
compared with analysts=E2=80=99 average estimate of $42.2 billion. Shares r=
ose 7.1% in premarket trading before New York exchanges opened on Wednesday=
. If the gains hold, it would mark the largest intraday move since February=
.

Google=E2=80=99s earnings call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4619735-a=
lphabet-inc-goog-q2-2023-earnings-call-transcript ) was also all about AI a=
ll of the time, but I didn=E2=80=99t find it particularly notable; there wa=
s, of course, the usual rhetoric about how AI has been infused in Google=E2=
=80=99s products for a long time, and the comments about generative AI comi=
ng to ads was pretty interesting. Chief Business Office Philipp Schindler s=
aid:

We=E2=80=99ve long said it=E2=80=99s all about reaching the right customer =
with the right creative at the right time. So later this year, automaticall=
y created assets, which are already generating headlines and descriptions f=
or search ads, will start using generative AI to create assets that are eve=
n more relevant to customer queries.

What this sounds like is that, in the not too distant future, headlines and=
 descriptions will be generated on-demand for ads; that=E2=80=99s pretty in=
credible, and a testament to Google=E2=80=99s infrastructural capabilities,=
 and yes, an example of how AI can make Google=E2=80=99s products better. W=
hat matters most to the Street, though, is that Google=E2=80=99s core busin=
ess is doing well; relief, in other words, appears to be a greater driver o=
f the stock than Microsoft=E2=80=99s theoretical promise.

I also want to note YouTube=E2=80=99s results; newly-promoted President Rut=
h Porat said:

Within Google Services, revenues were $66.3 billion, up 5%. Google Search a=
nd other advertising revenues of $42.6 billion in the quarter were up 5%, l=
ed by growth in retail. YouTube advertising revenues of $7.7 billion were u=
p 4%, driven by brand advertising, followed by direct response, reflecting =
further stabilization in spending by advertisers. Network advertising reven=
ues of $7.9 billion were down 5%. Other revenues were $8.1 billion, up 24%,=
 reflecting growth in YouTube non-advertising revenues, primarily from subs=
cription growth in YouTube Music Premium and YouTube TV, followed by growth=
 in hardware revenues, primarily driven by the launch of the Pixel 7a in th=
e second quarter. Finally, Play returned to positive growth in the second q=
uarter. TAC was $12.5 billion, up 3%. Google Services operating income was =
$23.5 billion, up 8%, and the operating margin was 35%.

